body: I'm pretty sure I fixed that today. Can you confirm?
Yep that works now!

I think it has to do with how different databases autocast and/or how people store dates as string.

I've been spending some time trying to figure out how to have sqlalchemy do the proper casting but haven't figured it out yet.

We may need for `is_dttm` columns to allow to define how the time constants should be casted when comparing to them...

@gbrian, I got the reason. Just setting `PYTHONPATH` before `fabmanager create-admin`, it will overwrite default config which setting `SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI = 'sqlite:////tmp/caravel.db`.

My project(renamed from panoramix-docker): https://github.com/wbchn/caravel-docker

Hi, this docker works like charm, take a look into the docker-compose.yml

https://hub.docker.com/r/amancevice/caravel/

@philippfrenzel  no docker for caravel(panoramix) last year, so i build this docker project.

`amancevice/caravel` is better, but it can not add admin automatic in first time, which we need auto-deploy to docker cluster or add to compose(we do not use it now).

I think this is a great user experience improvement, especially given this flow is pretty early in people using the tool. It certainly stumped me the first few times I came through the setup process.

Simple validation on the table page would be sufficient. Helper text combined with then polling the DB to check that the name is valid when unfocussing from the field and then providing a helpful error message would be sufficient.

@mistercrunch 
So right now whether a user can access a dashboard is determined by whether the role has the datasource access. It has nothing to do with whether the user is the owner of the slice or dashboard. Am I correct? Thanks

"Flow" is the right way I think about it. There isn't really an "onboarding" process for adding new data. If you look at my walkthrough, there are a lot of steps that say "ok, now go back to the [..]" which could happen automatically as redirects when the form is saved, etc. That can be improved upon even further - for instance, if there is only one table, automatically create that as the default table, if there are fields with "date_" in the name, automatically mark those as date fields, make text fields groupable by default, etc.. Little stuff like that would go a really long way.

I am still finding problem with this issue. I just updated to latest caravel.
Should I do anything to make this #283 fix to work?

![screenshot 2016-04-27 17 47 39](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1760989/14867722/447bc81a-0ca0-11e6-8a2b-bde7dda6ac81.png)
`Admin` and `Alpha` have access to all datasources, `Gamma` user need and extra role with specific datasource access to list and access dashboard and slices

I'm planning on making it such that only object owners can alter dashboards and slices. This PR added the possibility to add many owners to a dashboard or slice, but that is not taken into account yet. I opened issues to ask the Flask AppBuilder project on advice on how to implement that
#283 was not the right approach. we have yet to find a solution to this.
It'd be nice if someone could provide a new example dataset with unicode in it that we could load as an example in `data/__init__.py` and write unit tests against.

So in your plan it is only for the access control of editing dashboards/slices, right? Do you think it is good to have the view access control on whether a user can see a certain dashboard/slice, maybe like #357 ? Is it in any of your plans?

Hi,

After some digging in it seems that it is indeed to the realtime server issue/bug.
There's a piece of code that will not extract the metadata for segments less than 24 hours.  
After a day, i was able to refresh the metadata and was able to see data.

We don't use realtime, but we do a lot of small batches and then one big daily batch.
